FROM OUR CORRESPONDENT

Why Finns came top in the happiness ratings four times in a row

Don’t expect to see too many smiling faces, just a quiet trust in one another

Oliver Moody, Helsinki
Sunday December 12 2021, 6.00pm GMT, The Times
BPC > Full article text: https://archive.today?run=1&url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/why-finns-came-top-in-the-happiness-ratings-four-times-in-a-row-wdwmqlx8p
BPC > Full article text: https://archive.today?run=1&url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/why-finns-came-top-in-the-happiness-ratings-four-times-in-a-row-wdwmqlx8p

In the Kalevala, Finland’s national epic, the master blacksmith Ilmarinen crafts a mysterious magical artefact called the Sampo for the evil witch-queen of the north.

She jealously hides it behind nine locks and buries it deep in the earth, where it sits churning out wealth for her people until it is eventually stolen, smashed and scattered across the seabed.

Today, Finland seems to have got its Sampo back. This year the country came top of international happiness rankings for the fourth time in a row. Much like the witch-queen’s prosperity, the mechanisms behind this are a bit obscure.

It is not quite 8.30am and Frank Martela, a philosopher at Aalto University who specialises in the meaning of life, is getting his PowerPoint presentation ready in a hotel conference room. Dressed in a floral-print shirt, a natty waistcoat and a brown felt fedora, he is as cheerful as an off-duty hobbit. His first slide shows the jubilant scenes around the Havis Amanda fountain in Helsinki after Finland won the ice hockey world cup in 2019. Beneath it is the same view after Finland was named the happiest country. The square is deserted.

“One thing was immediately noticeable,” he said. “The Finnish people were not too happy about it. The main emotion people had was: ‘No, that can’t be true, there must be something wrong with the methodology.’ I guess [we] have a bit of a melancholic self-image that we like to listen to a very heavy-metal kind of music or tales about far-distant lands we never go to or people we will never meet again.”

The answer is that the surveys are not measuring joy or ecstasy but simply how satisfied people are in general. “If you walk through the streets, people aren’t smiling as much as some other cities you might have gone to in the past,” Martela said. “But if you ask them, they might say, ‘Yeah, I’m quite satisfied with my life. Nothing bothers me too much.’ ”

A rare moment of public exuberance after Finland won the ice hockey world cup
KIMMO BRANDT/EPA-EFE/SHUTTERSTOCK/REX FEATURES

Martela and his colleagues have spent several years burrowing into the data. The explanation they have come up with is that in societies whose citizens trust one another enough to shell out a large share of their income in taxes, you tend to get pretty good public services and correspondingly low levels of dissatisfaction. Yet that only raises another question: why do the Finns and other Scandinavians have so much trust in the state and the people around them?

This is where another theory comes in. Foreign economists, especially from the US, have often suggested that the real factor underpinning Scandinavia’s happiness is its history of ethnic and cultural homogeneity.

One thing Finland, Denmark, Sweden and Norway all have in common is their strong post-war welfare states. As non-European immigrants have begun to arrive in large numbers in the past five or six years, even mainstream politicians have started to depict them as an existential threat to the Nordic social contract. Anu Partanen, author of The Nordic Theory of Everything, gives that notion short shrift. “The assumption there is that homogeneity equals agreement, and everyone who shares the same ethnicity, religion and historical roots is one big happy family,” she said. “But that isn’t the case in Finland at all.”

Partanen argues that the solidarity was forged by the Finnish state after a grim civil war between socialists and capitalists following independence from Russia in 1917.

“The universal social policies that Finns enjoy today, which were created after the Second World War, were in fact a response to this brutal class conflict where Finns were literally murdering one another,” she said. “They were an effort to create some equality and unity where there was none.”
